{
  "text": "Confinement is associated with a lower BCS, with confined dogs being 1.7 times more likely to have a lower BCS than unconfined dogs. Although confinement, as defined in this study, was highly variable (with regards to the length of time dogs were confined and the frequency that they were released), in general it was observed that dogs that were tied up were often neglected. See [CITATION_1] for a full discussion on these issues.",
